Here's a clean implementation using the MVVM Community Toolkit, which eliminates boilerplate:

```csharp
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.ComponentModel;
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.Input;

namespace YourApp.ViewModels;

public partial class ProductDetailViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _name = string.Empty;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private decimal _price;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _isAvailable;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _isBusy;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task LoadAsync()
    {
        if (IsBusy) return;

        try
        {
            IsBusy = true;

            // Replace with your actual data service call
            await Task.Delay(500);

            Name = "Widget Pro";
            Price = 29.99m;
            IsAvailable = true;
        }
        finally
        {
            IsBusy = false;
        }
    }
}
```

**How it works:**

- `[ObservableProperty]` — source-generates public properties (`Name`, `Price`, etc.) with `INotifyPropertyChanged` calls, from the backing fields.
- `[RelayCommand]` — source-generates `LoadCommand` (an `IAsyncRelayCommand`) from `LoadAsync()`, which also exposes `LoadCommand.IsRunning` for free.
- The class must be `partial` so the generator can emit the other half.

**XAML binding example:**

```xml
<Label Text="{Binding Name}" />
<Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='{0:C}'}" />
<Switch IsToggled="{Binding IsAvailable}" />
<Button Text="Load" Command="{Binding LoadCommand}" />
<ActivityIndicator IsRunning="{Binding IsBusy}" IsVisible="{Binding IsBusy}" />
```

**NuGet package needed:** `CommunityToolkit.Mvvm` (add via `dotnet add package CommunityToolkit.Mvvm`).
